AQA A-Level Chemistry вЂ” Practical Guide
Safety and Hazards
Hazard	Precaution
Irritant (dilute acid/alkalis)	Wear goggles
Corrosive (stronger acids/alkalis)	Wear goggles
Flammable	Keep away from naked flames
Toxic	Wear gloves, avoid skin contact, wash hands after use
Oxidising	Keep away from flammable/easily oxidised materials
Hazardous substances in low concentrations or amounts will not pose the same risks as the pure substance.

General Techniques
Heating in a Crucible
Used for measuring mass loss in thermal decomposition reactions and mass gain when reacting magnesium in oxygen.

Example reaction: CaSOв‚„В·xHв‚‚O(s) в†’ CaSOв‚„(s) + xHв‚‚O(g)

Method:

Weigh an empty clean dry crucible and lid
Add 2 g of hydrated calcium sulfate to the crucible and weigh again
Heat strongly with a Bunsen for a couple of minutes
Allow to cool
Weigh the crucible and contents again
Heat crucible again and reweigh until you reach a constant mass (ensures reaction is complete)
Key points:

The lid prevents loss of solid from the crucible but should be loose fitting to allow gas to escape
Large amounts (e.g. 50 g) should not be used вЂ” decomposition likely to be incomplete
Small amounts (e.g. 0.100 g) should not be used вЂ” percentage uncertainties in weighing will be too high
The crucible must be dry вЂ” a wet crucible would give inaccurate results (mass loss too large as water lost on heating)
Worked Example 1: 3.51 g of hydrated zinc sulfate heated в†’ 1.97 g anhydrous zinc sulfate. Find x in ZnSOв‚„В·xHв‚‚O.

Mass of Hв‚‚O = 3.51 вЂ“ 1.97 = 1.54 g
Moles ZnSOв‚„ = 1.97 / 161.5 = 0.0122
Moles Hв‚‚O = 1.54 / 18 = 0.0856
Ratio = 0.0856 / 0.0122 = 7
x = 7
Using a Gas Syringe
Used for measuring volume of gas (to work out moles or follow reaction rates).

Key points:

Volume of gas depends on pressure and temperature вЂ” record both
Moles of gas calculated using ideal gas equation: PV = nRT
Draw diagrams without gaps where gas could escape
Draw measurement markings on the barrel
Potential errors:

Gas escapes before bung inserted
Syringe sticks
Soluble gases (COв‚‚, SOв‚‚) вЂ” true amount of gas not measured
Method for calculating Mr of a volatile liquid (e.g. propanone):

Extract 0.20 cmВі of propanone into a hypodermic syringe and measure its mass
Using hand protection, remove a gas syringe from the oven and note the volume of air already in the barrel (~5 cmВі)
Inject propanone through the self-seal cap into the barrel вЂ” plunger moves immediately
Put the gas syringe back into the oven
Measure the mass of the empty hypodermic syringe immediately
After a few minutes, measure volume of gas, record oven temperature and room pressure
Worked Example 2: 0.150 g of volatile liquid, 70В°C, 100 kPa, 80 cmВі

100 kPa = 100 000 Pa; 80 cmВі = 0.00008 mВі; T = 343 K
Moles = PV/RT = (100 000 Г— 0.00008) / (8.31 Г— 343) = 0.00281 mol
Mr = 0.15 / 0.00281 = 53.4 g molвЃ»В№
Measuring Mass Accurately
Measure mass on 2 or 3 d.p. balance of a weighing bottle with the required quantity of solid
Empty into reaction vessel/flask
Reweigh the now empty weighing bottle
Subtract to give exact mass actually added
Making a Standard Solution
Weigh the sample bottle containing the required mass of solid on a 2 d.p. balance
Transfer to beaker; reweigh empty sample bottle; record the difference in mass
Add 100 cmВі of distilled water to the beaker; stir with a glass rod to dissolve (heat gently if needed)
Pour solution into a 250 cmВі volumetric flask via a funnel
Rinse beaker, funnel and glass rod вЂ” add washings to the flask
Make up to the mark with distilled water using a dropping pipette for the last few drops
Invert flask several times to ensure uniform solution
Key points:

Fill so the bottom of the meniscus sits on the line on the neck of the flask
Do not heat or put hot solutions in the volumetric flask вЂ” heat causes expansion and incorrect volume
Dilutions
Pipette 25 cmВі of original solution into a 250 cmВі volumetric flask
Make up to the mark with distilled water using a dropping pipette for last few drops
Invert flask several times to ensure uniform solution
Using a volumetric pipette is more accurate than a measuring cylinder because it has a smaller uncertainty.

Filtration
Gravitational filtration: Use if small amounts of solid are formed. Filter paper in a filter funnel; filtrate collects below.

Vacuum (Buchner) filtration: Use if larger amounts of solid are formed. Buchner funnel + flask connected to water pump to reduce pressure and speed up filtration. Buchner flask has thicker glass walls to cope with the vacuum.

AQA expect filter paper to be drawn on diagrams for both types.

Required Practical 1: AcidвЂ“Base Titration
General Method
Rinse equipment: burette with acid, pipette with alkali, conical flask with distilled water
Pipette 25 cmВі of alkali into conical flask
Touch surface of alkali with pipette (ensures correct amount added)
Add acid solution from burette; ensure jet space is filled with acid
Add a few drops of indicator; refer to colour change at end point
Use a white tile underneath to help observe colour change
Add acid to alkali whilst swirling; add dropwise at end point
Note burette reading before and after addition
Repeat until at least 2 concordant results (within 0.1 cmВі of each other)
Using the Pipette
Rinse pipette with substance to go in it
Fill to the mark вЂ” bottom of meniscus on the line
Touch surface of solution with pipette to ensure correct amount
Small amount left in pipette is accounted for by calibration вЂ” do not force it out
Using the Burette
Rinse with the substance that will be put in it (prevents dilution/reaction with residual water)
Don't leave the funnel in the burette вЂ” drops may fall during titration в†’ false reading
Fill jet space and remove air bubbles
If jet space fills during titration в†’ larger than expected titre
Read the bottom of the meniscus
Record to 2 d.p. ending in 0.00 or 0.05 (0.05 cmВі = 1 drop)
Indicators
Indicator	Alkali Colour	End Point	Acid Colour	Best Used With
Phenolphthalein	Pink	Pink just disappears	Colourless	Strong alkalis (e.g. NaOH)
Methyl orange	Yellow	Orange	Red	Strong acids (e.g. HCl)
Only add a few drops вЂ” indicators are weak acids and too much will affect the result.

Additional Points
Distilled water can be added to the conical flask during titration to wash sides вЂ” does not affect result (doesn't change moles of acid)
Only distilled water should be used to wash out conical flasks between titrations
A conical flask is used in preference to a beaker вЂ” easier to swirl without spilling
Recording Results
Titration	1	2	3
Initial burette reading (cmВі)	0.50	2.50	1.55
Final burette reading (cmВі)	24.50	27.00	25.95
Titre (cmВі)	24.00	24.50	24.40
Average titre = (24.50 + 24.40) / 2 = 24.45 cmВі (only average concordant results)

Common Titration Equations
CHв‚ѓCOв‚‚H + NaOH в†’ CHв‚ѓCOв‚‚вЃ»NaвЃғ + Hв‚‚O
Hв‚‚SOв‚„ + 2NaOH в†’ Naв‚‚SOв‚„ + 2Hв‚‚O
