Uncertainty
Apparatus Uncertainties
Apparatus	Uncertainty
Balance (3 d.p.)	В±0.001 g
Volumetric flask	В±0.1 cmВі
25 cmВі pipette	В±0.1 cmВі
Burette (start + end + endpoint)	В±0.15 cmВі
Analogue scale: Reading (one judgement) = В±0.5 of smallest scale division. Measurement (two judgements) = В±1 of smallest scale division.

Digital scale: Uncertainty = В±resolution of apparatus.

Percentage Uncertainty
% uncertainty = (uncertainty / measurement) Г— 100

Total % apparatus uncertainty = sum of all individual equipment uncertainties.

Reducing Uncertainties
In titrations: Replace measuring cylinders with pipettes/burettes (lower uncertainty). Make titre larger by increasing volume/concentration in conical flask or decreasing concentration in burette.

In weighing: Use a more accurate balance or a larger mass. Weigh before and after then calculate difference.

Percentage Difference (Accuracy Check)
% difference = |actual вЂ“ calculated| / actual Г— 100

If % apparatus uncertainty < % difference в†’ discrepancy due to other errors
If % apparatus uncertainty > % difference в†’ no discrepancy; all errors explained by equipment sensitivity
Required Practical 2: Measurement of an Enthalpy Change
Calorimetric Method
Equation: Q = m Г— cв‚љ Г— О”T

Where: Q (J), m (g), cв‚љ (J gвЃ»В№ KвЃ»В№), О”T (K)

Assumes: heat capacity of solution = water (4.18 J gвЃ»В№ KвЃ»В№); density of solution = 1 g cmвЃ»Ві

General Method
Wash equipment with the solutions to be used; dry the cup
Put polystyrene cup in a beaker for insulation and support
Measure volumes of solutions with volumetric pipettes; transfer to insulated cup
Clamp thermometer with bulb immersed in solution
Measure initial temperature every minute for 2вЂ“3 minutes
At minute 3, transfer second reagent (if solid, weigh using before-and-after method)
Stir mixture
Record temperature every minute for several minutes
Extrapolation Method (for slow reactions)
If reaction is slow, cooling occurs simultaneously. Take readings at regular intervals and extrapolate the temperature curve back to the time of addition. Plot temperature vs time; draw two best-fit lines (before and after addition); extrapolate both to the addition time.

Errors
Energy transfer to/from surroundings
Approximation in specific heat capacity (assumes all solutions = water)
Neglecting heat capacity of calorimeter
Reaction may be incomplete or slow
Density of solution assumed same as water
Calculating О”H from Experimental Data
Calculate Q = m Г— cв‚љ Г— О”T
Calculate moles of reactant not in excess
О”H = Q / moles
Add sign (exothermic = negative) and unit (kJ molвЃ»В№)
Worked Example 6: Displacement Reaction
25.0 cmВі of 0.20 M CuSOв‚„ reacted with 0.01 mol Zn (excess). Temperature increased 7.0В°C.

Q = 25 Г— 4.18 Г— 7 = 731.5 J
Moles CuSOв‚„ = 0.2 Г— 25/1000 = 0.005 mol (not in excess)
О”H = 731.5 / 0.005 = 146 300 J molвЃ»В№ = 146 kJ molвЃ»В№
Temperature increased в†’ exothermic в†’ О”H = вЂ“146 kJ molвЃ»В№
Note: mass = mass of CuSOв‚„ solution only (do not include Zn powder)

Worked Example 7: Neutralisation
25.0 cmВі of 2.0 M HCl + 25.0 cmВі of 2.0 M NaOH. Temperature increased 13.5В°C.

Q = 50 Г— 4.18 Г— 13.5 = 2821.5 J (mass = acid + alkali = 50 g)
Moles HCl = 2 Г— 25/1000 = 0.05 mol
О”H = 2821.5 / 0.05 = 56 430 J molвЃ»В№
О”H = вЂ“56.4 kJ molвЃ»В№
