Required Practical 3: Rate of Reaction vs Temperature
Experiment: Sodium Thiosulfate and Hydrochloric Acid
Naв‚‚Sв‚‚Oв‚ѓ + 2HCl в†’ 2NaCl + SOв‚‚ + S + Hв‚‚O

Rate measured as 1/time where time = time for a cross underneath to disappear (due to sulfur cloudiness). This approximates initial rate because the amount of sulfur to obscure the cross is constant in each experiment.

Method:

Measure 10 cmВі of 0.2 M HCl and 10 cmВі of Naв‚‚Sв‚‚Oв‚ѓ in separate measuring cylinders; put in separate boiling tubes
Use a water bath to get both solutions to the chosen temperature
Place flask on the large cross; add Naв‚‚Sв‚‚Oв‚ѓ first, then add HCl and start stopwatch; swirl to mix
Stop the clock when the cross disappears; note the time
Repeat for four more temperatures (maximum 70В°C)
Analysis вЂ” Calculating Activation Energy
The Arrhenius equation rearranges to: ln k = constant вЂ“ Ea/(RT)

Since k в€қ rate: ln(rate) в‰€ ln(1/t)

Plot ln(1/t) vs 1/T в†’ straight line with gradient = вЂ“Ea/R

в€ө Ea = вЂ“gradient Г— R (8.31)

